<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-705-768  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 705 768.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  Oct 1989 v6 n10 pS47(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>It's time to consider fiber-optic cable. (includes related articleon SunRiver Corp. design)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hurst, Rebecca.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber-optic cabling is likely to gain prominence in futurenetworking schemes because it offers superior performance,security, and data integrity over coaxial or twisted-pair cable.andO;It is more expensive than other types of cabling, and the extentto which businesses can justify the higher cost depends on theirsize and on their existing networks.andP;  Coaxial cable can carry500M-bps and twisted-pair wire about 16M-bps, but fiber opticcables can carry over 1,000M-bps with an error rate of 1 in 10billion.andP;  Fiber optic cabling supports all network architecturesand eliminates data corruption caused by electronic disturbancesbecause it is dielectric.andP;  Installation, added hardware, and testequipment account for much of the additional cost of fiber-opticcabling.andP;  Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI) standard supportis widely available in cables and is expected to lower the cost.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsLocal Area NetworksConnectivityData IntegrityData Transfer RateData Security.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Fiber-optic cable consists of two parts (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>